1) Find $$ a, b $$ and $$ c $$ so that following set of vectors is orthogonal $$ \pmatrix{ 2 \\ 1 \\ -1}, \pmatrix{ a \\ 1 \\ -1 }, $$ and $$ \pmatrix{ b \\ 3 \\ c } $$. What has to be done to make the set orthonormal. 

$$ 2(a)+1(1)+(-1)(-1) = 0 \implies 2a+2 = 0 \implies a = -1 $$

$$ 2(b)+1(3)+(-1)(c) = 0 \implies 2(3-c)+3-c = 0 \implies 9-3c = 0 \implies c = 3 $$

$$ ab+1(3)+(-1)(c) = 0 \implies -b+3-c = 0 \implies 3-c = b \implies b = 0 $$

$$ \therefore a = -1 \ , \ b = 0 \ , \ c=3 $$



>   $$ 2(-1) + 1 + 1 = 0 \checkmark $$

>   $$ 2(0) + 3 - 3 = 0 \checkmark $$

>   $$ (-1)(0) + 3 - (3) = 0 \checkmark$$

$$ v_1 =  \pmatrix{ 2 \\ 1 \\ -1} \ , \ v_2 = \pmatrix{ -1 \\ 1 \\ -1 } \ , \ v_3 = \pmatrix{ 0 \\ 3 \\ 3 }$$

$$ u_1 = \cfrac{v_1}{\Vert v_1 \Vert} = \cfrac{1}{\sqrt{2^2 + 1^2 + (-1)^2}} \pmatrix{ 2 \\ 1 \\ -1 } = \cfrac{1}{\sqrt{6}} \pmatrix{ 2 \\ 1 \\ -1} $$

$$ u_2 = \cfrac{v_2}{\Vert v_2 \Vert} = \cfrac{1}{\sqrt{(-1)^2 + 1^2 + (-1)^2}} \pmatrix{ -1 \\ 1 \\ -1 } = \cfrac{1}{\sqrt{3}} \pmatrix{ -1 \\ 1 \\ -1} $$

$$ u_3 = \cfrac{v_3}{\Vert v_3 \Vert} = \cfrac{1}{\sqrt{0^2 + 3^2 + (3^2}} \pmatrix{ 0 \\ 3 \\ 3 } = \cfrac{1}{3\sqrt{2}} \pmatrix{ 2 \\ 1 \\ -1} $$










